Covertech Fabricating, Inc. v. TVM Bldg. Prods. , 855 F.3d 163, 170 (3d Cir.2017). “In assessing the rightful ownership of the … mark, the District Court relied on the ‘first use test,’ which determines initial ownership by asking which party was the first to use an unregistered trademark in commerce. [W]e conclude … the first use test was not the correct test given the unique context of the manufacturer-distributor relationship…. At 171-72: [W]here initial ownership between a manufacturer and its exclusive distributor is at issue and no contract exists, the manufacturer is the presumptive trademark owner unless the distributor rebuts that presumption using a multi-factor balancing test designed to examine the distribution agreement in effect between the parties. The six factors that should be considered are: (1) ‘[w]hich party invented or created the mark’; (2) ‘[w]hich party first affixed the mark to goods sold’; (3) ‘[w]hich party's name appeared on packaging and promotional materials in conjunction with the mark’; (4) ‘[w]hich party exercised control over the nature and quality of goods on which the mark appeared’; (5) ‘[t]o which party did customers look as standing behind the goods, e.g., which party received complaints for defects and made appropriate replacement or refund’; and (6) ‘[w]hich party paid for advertising and promotion of the trademarked product.’ [¶] Our adoption of this test is also consistent with our sister Circuits, which, when asked to determine ownership in this context, have endorsed some version of the [treatise] test…. While some courts have distilled [treatise’s] six factors to four, … and others have varied the language, … all have cited either to … treatise itself or to cases that do so, applying the [treatise] test with only minor variations across the federal courts.” See also
TMT N. Am., Inc. v. Magic Touch GmbH , 124 F.3d 876, 884 n.4 (7th Cir.1997);
Sengoku Works Ltd. v. RMC Int'l , 96 F.3d 1217, 1220 (9th Cir.1996).
